Atherosclerosis is the principal cause of most cardiovascular disease (Libby, 2001). It apparently results from chronic injury to the arteries (Fig. 12.3
). Although associated with several independent factors, most damage develops as a result of the oxidation of lipids in a special subgroup of cholesterol–apoproteins complexes, the low-density lipoproteins (LDLs). Because of the hydrophobic nature of cholesterol and triglycerides, their transfer via the blood requires a special transport vehicle. As illustrated in Fig. 12.4
, lipoprotein complexes consist of an outer membrane of phospholipids, in which apoproteins and free cholesterol occur. They enclose a hydrophobic core possessing numerous triglycerides and cholesteryl esters. The specific apoproteins in the complex regulate the metabolism of the associated lipids.
